# Sampling done already in Amber MD
# Pre-select a generous solvent region around the solute and let the
# subsequent Python step refine that to a true frame-wise first shell
# around the solute surface.
#
# Why this two-step approach:
#   1) cpptraj closest keeps a fixed NUMBER of waters, not a true first shell.
#   2) frame-updating distance masks in cpptraj are only supported by the mask
#      action, which is awkward for directly writing the desired per-frame XYZ.
# So here cpptraj only produces a safe preselection; the exact first-shell
# trimming is done afterwards on each split XYZ frame.

parm ${name}.parm7
trajin ${name}_md.mdcrd 1 last 10

# Make the solute whole and keep nearby solvent imaged around it.
autoimage
solvent ${solvent_mask}

# Diagnostic only: shell statistics around the solute.
watershell :1 out ${name}_watershell.dat lower ${shell_lower} upper ${shell_upper} ${solvent_mask}

# Keep a generous number of closest waters so the later Python trimming has
# enough candidates even for larger metal complexes.
# 'first' measures to the first atom of the solvent molecule and is the
# recommended fast mode for standard water models.
closest ${shell_preselect_waters} :1 first closestout ${name}_closest.dat

center :1 mass origin
image origin center

trajout ${name}_frame.xyz xyz ftype namexyz multi
run